## What happened

.NET 11 removed the managed DSA fallback on macOS. Because Apple's **Security.framework** has never provided a native DSA implementation, `DSA.Create()` now throws **`PlatformNotSupportedException`** on macOS. Linux (OpenSSL) and Windows (CNG) still have native DSA support, so they continue to work.

## How to fix it

You have two practical options:

### Option 1 — BouncyCastle (recommended for verify-only)

Use a managed crypto library that works on all platforms:

```bash
dotnet add package BouncyCastle.Cryptography
```

```csharp
using Org.BouncyCastle.Crypto.Parameters;
using Org.BouncyCastle.Security;

bool VerifyDsaSignature(byte[] data, byte[] signature, DsaPublicKeyParameters pubKey)
{
    var signer = SignerUtilities.GetSigner("SHA-1withDSA");
    signer.Init(forSigning: false, pubKey);
    signer.BlockUpdate(data, 0, data.Length);
    return signer.VerifySignature(signature);
}
```

### Option 2 — Use OpenSSL explicitly on macOS

Install OpenSSL via Homebrew and use `DSAOpenSsl`:

```bash
brew install openssl
```

```csharp
using System.Security.Cryptography;

DSA CreateDsa()
{
    if (OperatingSystem.IsMacOS())
        return new DSAOpenSsl(); // from System.Security.Cryptography.OpenSsl
    return DSA.Create();
}
```

### Long-term recommendation

DSA is a legacy algorithm (FIPS 186-4 deprecated it). Plan to **migrate signatures to ECDSA or Ed25519**, which are supported natively on all platforms.
